Great Island 4-6 June

Receiver Range Testing

On the afternoon of June 4th, I activated a test VHF tag while standing at the receiver station. I then kept that tag with a GPS, which was on and running whenever the tag was in motion (i.e, not in the cabin). On June 5th, we walked a lap of the islandâs edge with the GPS and test tag. I then deactivated the tag after walking back to the receiver station on 6 June.

Simple VHF visualization

Based on the power level of the detections, we can see three trips near the receiver, interrupted by long stays at the cabin (which is just barely in range of the southeast-facing antenna). If we look at just our lap around the island on June 5th, we can see more detail:

We spent quite a bit of time northeast of the tower, but also quite a bit of time down in the low valleys between the ridges of the island, where I might not expect reception to be very good.

Combining VHF and GPS points

Here is the GPS track from our trip. The receiver stationâs location is shown as a red diamond. I went between the cabin and the receiver a few times, made one lap around the northern part of the island, and made one trip to the eastern face that was followed by cutting back through the forest. The next step is to connect these GPS points with the VHF detections.

gps_track <- gps_track %>% 
  mutate(bin = round_date(datetime, "1 min"))

bins <- as.list(unique(gps_track$bin))

filtered_vhf <- vhf %>% 
  mutate(bin = round_date(datetime, "1 min")) %>%
  filter(bin %in% bins) %>% 
  group_by(bin, direction) %>% #preserves one detection from each antenna in each bin
  slice(which.min(datetime))#takes the first detection from each direction in each bin

vhf_positions <- left_join(filtered_vhf, gps_track, by = join_by(closest(datetime > datetime))) %>% 
  rename(datetime = datetime.x) %>% 
  select(date:direction, lat:ele)

Now we have a dataframe of VHF detections with associated latitudes and longitudes. We can map those referenced detections where the points reflect the location of the tag at the time of transmission, with colors for 1) which antenna received the transmission and 2) the power level of the transmission. Our full GPS track is laid underneath the GPS-referenced detections, so you can see areas where we dipped out of range of the receiver.
